From: Octopus Orchestrator upstream PR draft wave (M0-25)
Subject: [PATCH] config: wire loadOctoConfig into the core loader

Plumb the `octo:` config block at the root of openclaw.json into the
core config loader. When present, loadConfig() dispatches to
loadOctoConfig() from src/octo/config/loader.ts (M0-11) to obtain a
validated OctoConfig, which is attached to the resolved OpenClawConfig
under a new optional `octo` field alongside other subsystem configs
(channels, cron, tools, hooks, memory, mcp).

loadOctoConfig is pure: it takes the already-parsed root config object
as input and performs NO file I/O, env substitution, or include
resolution. Those concerns remain the core loader's, upstream of the
dispatch point. The core loader does NOT redefine the schema — the
single source of truth is src/octo/config/schema.ts (M0-06).

Default behavior when `octo:` is missing: the loader resolves to
{ enabled: false, ... }, and the octo subsystem is completely dormant —
no state dirs, no method dispatch (octo.* handlers return not_enabled),
no CLI entry, no cron/hook/tool registration. Existing 2026.4.8
deployments upgrade with zero behavior change.

Malformed `octo:` blocks cause startup to fail with a clear error
message listing the failing paths. Matches the core loader's strict-
validation policy — no silent fallback to defaults (OCTO-DEC-027,
CONFIG.md §Validation).

Draft authored against upstream commit 9ece252.

